"However, if you don’t have anything important in the private volume "
"(likely for a template), then you can work around this by just resetting "
"the private volume with :samp:`qvm-volume import --no-resize "
"{<template>}:private /dev/null`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:222
#: a64806bb046e46a1a12157941373c2fd
msgid ""
"The saved revision of the volumes must be uncompromised. With the default"
" ``revisions_to_keep=1`` for the root volume, you must **not** have "
"started the template since the compromising action."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:227
#: 053e712fbfe64b66a203c6bdbf0d110b
msgid "Updates proxy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:229
#: 69e2eaa5c4b24b47a49c17860cebf1da
msgid ""
"Updates proxy is a service which allows access from package managers "
"configured to use the proxy by default, but can be used by any other "
"program that accepts proxy arguments. The purpose of the proxy, instead "
"of direct network access, is meant to mitigate user errors of using "
"applications such as the browser in the template. Not necessarily what "
"part of the network they can access, but only to applications trusted by "
"the user, configured to use the proxy. The http proxy (tinyproxy) does "
"not filter traffic because it is hard to list all the repository mirrors "
"and keep that list up to date). it also does not cache anything."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:231
#: 2fa7cd57d9cf4c52b326a27060831acd
msgid ""
"The proxy is running in selected VMs (by default all the NetVMs (1)) and "
"intercepts traffic directed to 127.0.0.1:8082. Thanks to such "
"configuration all the VMs can use the same proxy address. If the VM is "
"configured to have access to the updates proxy (2), the startup scripts "
"will automatically configure dnf/apt to really use the proxy (3). Also "
"access to updates proxy is independent of any other firewall settings (VM"
" will have access to updates proxy, even if policy is set to block all "
"the traffic)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:233
#: 2e335ab0a4f5413c9c97d31d15abcf0b
msgid ""
"There are two services (``qvm-service``, :doc:`service framework </user"
"/advanced-topics/qubes-service>`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:235
#: 9aa0173b627a49689e91162a678bf6bd
msgid ""
"``qubes-updates-proxy`` (and its deprecated name: ``qubes-yum-proxy``) - "
"a service providing a proxy for templates - by default enabled in NetVMs "
"(especially: sys-net)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:237
#: 0481af931c214fffa3957cd8da7c0c36
msgid ""
"``updates-proxy-setup`` (and its deprecated name: ``yum-proxy-setup``) - "
"use a proxy provided by another VM (instead of downloading updates "
"directly), enabled by default in all templates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:239
#: 7f525c05578e4fec86a8c2f3c1031af2
msgid ""
"Both the old and new names work. The defaults listed above are applied if"
" the service is not explicitly listed in the services tab."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:242
#: baf7feb530a94781a9eb884d5aad8956
msgid "Technical details"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:244
#: 5774063ceedb45679ce43d115c80f00e
msgid ""
"The updates proxy uses RPC/qrexec. The proxy is configured in qrexec "
"policy in dom0: ``/etc/qubes-rpc/policy/qubes.UpdatesProxy``. By default "
"this is set to sys-net and/or sys-whonix, depending on firstboot choices."
" This new design allows for templates to be updated even when they are "
"not connected to any NetVM."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/how-to-guides/how-to-install-software.rst:246
#: f40170234d8745ba95e900c6a41f7d21
msgid ""
"Example policy file in R4.1 (with Whonix installed, but not set as "
"default UpdateVM for all templates):"
msgstr ""

